      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between hot standby and warm standby in solar SCADA?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Hot standby means the secondary solar SCADA server is fully synchronized with the primary in real time. Failover is automatic and takes seconds, with no data loss. Warm standby means the secondary is running and periodically synced, but not in real time, and failover takes minutes and some data may be lost. Cold standby means a spare server exists but must be powered on and configured manually, which takes hours. Hot standby is the correct choice for utility-scale solar plants operating under performance guarantees or grid frequency response obligations."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does solar SCADA downtime cost per hour?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The direct cost of solar SCADA downtime depends on plant size, power price, and whether the plant is operating under a power purchase agreement with availability penalties. A 100 MW AC solar plant producing at 25% capacity factor loses roughly 25 MWh per hour of unplanned SCADA outage. At $40/MWh that is $1,000 per hour in lost generation value, before counting availability penalty clauses or grid compliance violations that compound the exposure."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does NERC CIP require solar SCADA redundancy?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "NERC CIP does not mandate a specific redundancy architecture, but CIP-014 requires that responsible entities protect facilities whose loss could significantly impact grid reliability. Practically, any solar plant classified as a high or medium BES Cyber System under CIP-002 must implement controls that minimize the risk of extended SCADA outages affecting grid operations. Most compliance auditors expect hot standby or warm standby architectures for plants above 75 MW with grid interconnection obligations."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What network redundancy is needed for solar SCADA high availability?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Solar SCADA high availability requires redundancy at three network layers: the server layer (primary and standby servers on separate hardware), the LAN layer (redundant managed switches with rapid spanning tree protocol), and the WAN layer (dual communication paths, for example, fiber as the primary path and cellular as the backup). Losing any single one of these layers should not cause a complete SCADA outage. The communication path to the utility is especially critical: DNP3 or OPC DA links to the utility EMS must remain available even when the plant's internal network is partially degraded."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does IEC 61850 relate to solar SCADA redundancy?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "IEC 61850 defines communication standards for substation automation, including the Parallel Redundancy Protocol (PRP) and High-availability Seamless Redundancy (HSR) protocols that support zero-packet-loss network switching. In solar SCADA architectures using IEC 61850 at the substation level, PRP and HSR provide sub-millisecond failover for protection and control traffic. For plants with digital substation equipment, designing the solar SCADA LAN to support IEC 61850-based redundancy protocols during the commissioning phase prevents expensive retrofit work later."
        }
      },
