    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should solar SCADA use Modbus TCP or DNP3?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The answer depends on where in the solar SCADA architecture the protocol is used. Modbus TCP is the right choice for inverter and tracker polling within the plant. 80 to 90% of solar field devices natively speak Modbus, making it the universal field device language. DNP3 is the right choice for the utility interface, substation IEDs, and any data path where timestamps, event buffering, or utility compliance reporting is required. Most utility-scale solar SCADA systems run both: Modbus TCP at the field device layer and DNP3 at the utility communication layer."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the main difference between Modbus TCP and DNP3?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Modbus TCP is a simple request-response protocol with no built-in timestamps, no event buffering, and no authentication. It excels at polling many devices quickly with low overhead. DNP3 (IEEE 1815) is a purpose-built SCADA protocol with timestamps on every data point, unsolicited event reporting, class-based polling, file transfer, and optional secure authentication (SA). DNP3 was designed specifically for SCADA applications where data integrity, event sequencing, and utility interoperability are required."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do utilities require DNP3 for solar plant interconnection?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Most US utilities with SCADA-level interconnection requirements specify DNP3 for the EMS communication link between the solar plant and the utility. This is because DNP3 provides timestamps and event buffering that let the utility reconstruct plant behavior during grid events, critical for frequency response verification and disturbance investigations. Some utilities also accept IEC 61850 GOOSE and MMS for plants using digital substation equipment. Check the utility's interconnection technical specification before finalizing the solar SCADA protocol stack."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Modbus TCP secure enough for solar SCADA?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Modbus TCP has no built-in security features: no authentication, no encryption, no message integrity checking. Any device on the same network that knows the Modbus TCP framing can read or write to a Modbus-enabled device. For solar SCADA systems that must comply with NERC CIP, Modbus TCP communication paths must be protected by network controls (firewalls, VLANs, IDS/IPS) rather than the protocol itself. DNP3 Secure Authentication version 5 (SAv5) adds HMAC-based message authentication without encryption, which satisfies most utility cybersecurity requirements for the SCADA link."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is IEEE 1815 and how does it relate to DNP3?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "IEEE 1815 is the formal standard that defines the DNP3 protocol specification. DNP3 originated in the early 1990s as a protocol for SCADA communication in electric utility distribution systems. IEEE adopted it as IEEE 1815 in 2010 (revised 2012), giving it a formal standards body backing. IEEE 1815-2012 defines the full DNP3 protocol including Basic, Level 1 through Level 4 device profiles, and Secure Authentication version 5. When a utility interconnection requirement says 'DNP3', it means the IEEE 1815 protocol."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can you mix Modbus TCP and DNP3 in the same solar SCADA system?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, and most utility-scale solar SCADA systems do exactly this. The plant controller or SCADA server polls inverters, trackers, and weather stations using Modbus TCP, then presents the aggregated plant-level data to the utility EMS using DNP3. The SCADA platform handles the protocol translation internally. This mixed architecture is standard practice and is why Nor-Cal Controls, REIG's hardware partner, recommends DNP3 for critical utility-facing devices and Modbus TCP for the bulk of field devices in the plant."
        }
      }
    ]
