        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How often must pyranometers be recalibrated for IEC 61724-1 compliance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "IEC 61724-1:2021 requires Class A pyranometers to be recalibrated every two years and inspected weekly in the field. Class A sensors drift at up to 0.8%/year (ISO 9060:2018); annual recalibration is best practice for acceptance test instruments. Class B sensors drift at up to 1.5%/year and follow manufacturer schedules, typically every two to three years."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What QC flags should a solar DAS apply to irradiance data?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A solar DAS should apply physical possible limits (PPL) and extremely rare limits (ERL) per BSRN, plus NREL QCRAD consistency checks cross-referencing GHI against DHI plus DNI cosine. These tiers catch out-of-range readings, soiling, and systematic drift that range checks alone miss. A 2017 study found 9.9% of 313 ground stations had faulty records that only Tier 3 caught."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does pyranometer soiling affect Performance Ratio calculations?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A soiled pyranometer underreads actual irradiance, shrinking the PR denominator and inflating the calculated ratio. Research (Solar Energy, Fuke & Kottantharayil, 2025) found pyranometer soiling rates at 36–48% of module soiling rates, causing PR to underestimate true module soiling by 30–43%. This suppresses the cleaning dispatch signal and reduces annual yield by a measurable revenue amount."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the financial impact of irradiance measurement errors at a utility-scale plant?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A 4% PR deviation at a 64 MW plant produces more than $1.8 million in lost revenue over 30 years (OTT HydroMet, 2026). Low-quality irradiance data costs approximately €10,000 per plant annually. Correct P90 resource data from defensible on-site measurements improves investor ROE by up to 10% (Vaisala, 2024). Met station commissioning costs a fraction of either figure."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What met station measurements are required for IEC 61724-1 Class A compliance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "IEC 61724-1:2021 Class A systems must measure GHI, POA irradiance, ambient temperature, and module temperature at minimum. Complete performance analysis requires DNI, DHI, wind speed, and wind direction as well. Bifacial systems additionally require rear-side irradiance sensors positioned at least 5 meters from row equator-facing ends to avoid edge brightening effects that bias rear-irradiance measurements by 10–20%."
        }
      }
