    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the ISA-18.2 acceptable alarm rate for solar SCADA?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "ISA-18.2 defines acceptable performance as fewer than 150 alarms per operator per day, with a maximum of 10 alarms in any 10-minute window before a system reaches flood status. Most new solar SCADA installations, without rationalization, routinely exceed 300 alarms per day during normal plant operation, more than double the acceptable threshold."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How many alarms per operator day is too many?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "ISA-18.2 classifies alarm rate in three tiers: acceptable is below 150 per day, very disturbing is 150 to 300 per day, and above 300 per day or more than 10 alarms in any 10-minute window constitutes a flood. At flood levels, operators statistically cannot respond to all alarms before the next wave arrives, causing critical events to be missed."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What causes chattering alarms in solar SCADA systems?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Chattering alarms occur when a sensor value oscillates across an alarm setpoint faster than operators can acknowledge. In solar SCADA, the most common cause is inverter AC voltage fluctuating near a setpoint during low-irradiance ramp events. Deadbanding, which adds a hysteresis band around the setpoint, eliminates most chattering alarms without masking real faults."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is deadbanding and how does it reduce nuisance alarms?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Deadbanding sets two thresholds instead of one: an alarm triggers when the value crosses the upper threshold, but only clears when the value drops below a lower threshold. The gap between them prevents rapid toggling. For inverter AC voltage alarms in solar SCADA, a deadband of 1 to 2 percent of rated voltage eliminates most chattering without masking real faults."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How long should alarm shelving last during solar maintenance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "ISA-18.2 requires shelved alarms to have a defined expiry time, not unlimited duration. For planned inverter maintenance windows, a 4-hour shelving limit is typical. Any shelved alarm that has not automatically restored within its window should trigger a management review. Indefinite shelving is the leading cause of hidden alarms that mask developing faults in solar plants."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "When should we run a solar SCADA alarm rationalization?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Alarm rationalization should be completed before factory acceptance testing so the solar SCADA commissioning team can validate alarm response procedures against a clean baseline. Re-rationalization is warranted when alarm rate consistently exceeds 150 per day, the top-10 tag list has not changed in 12 months, or O&M staff routinely acknowledge alarms without any follow-on action."
        }
      }
    ]
