  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is OTDR testing in fiber optic installation solar farm acceptance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "OTDR (Optical Time-Domain Reflectometer) testing sends a short optical pulse down a fiber run and measures the reflected signal to locate splices, connectors, and faults. In fiber optic installation solar farm acceptance, it verifies that every span meets IEC 61280-4-2 loss thresholds before the site reaches COD. It produces a permanent, auditable trace record for O&M handover."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What wavelengths are required for solar farm OS2 fiber OTDR testing?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "IEC 61280-4-2 requires testing at both 1310nm and 1550nm for OS2 single-mode fiber. Testing at 1310nm alone is insufficient: 1550nm traces are more sensitive to micro-bends and mechanical stress that develop over time in buried conduit. Solar farm commissioning reports must include both wavelength traces for every span to be defensible."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How long should the launch cable be for solar farm OTDR testing?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Use a 500m to 1000m launch cable for OS2 single-mode fiber. Modern OTDRs have an attenuation dead zone of 5 to 25 meters after a near-end reflection event. Without a launch cable of adequate length, the first splice and the near-end connector fall inside that dead zone and cannot be measured or documented. This is one of the most common acceptance failures on solar farm fiber runs."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the maximum splice and connector loss limits for solar farm fiber acceptance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Per IEC 61280-4-2, fusion splice loss must be at or below 0.10 dB for single-mode OS2 fiber. Connector pair insertion loss must be at or below 0.30 dB for UPC connectors and 0.20 dB for APC connectors. Any event that exceeds these thresholds is a rework trigger. Do not accept a site with out-of-spec splices on the promise that loss will improve in service."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What documentation should a fiber optic installation solar farm OTDR test produce?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A complete fiber optic installation solar farm OTDR acceptance package includes: bidirectional OTDR traces at 1310nm and 1550nm for every span, event tables with measured loss and reflectance for every splice and connector, a pass/fail verdict against IEC 61280-4-2 thresholds, a completed loss budget worksheet, and fiber identification labels cross-referenced to the cable schedule. All documents should be delivered in PDF and native OTDR format."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why does bidirectional OTDR testing matter for solar farm fiber acceptance?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Splice loss is directionally asymmetric. A fusion joint that reads 0.05 dB in one direction may read 0.12 dB in the opposite direction due to fiber geometry at the cleave. Bidirectional OTDR testing catches these asymmetries and produces the correct average loss value for each event. IEC 61280-4-2 requires bidirectional measurements for accurate splice characterization on single-mode OS2 runs."
        }
      }
    ]
  },
