  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the utility witness pack for solar SCADA commissioning?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The utility witness pack is the structured documentation bundle that records and supports utility acceptance testing for interconnection. It includes the point list comparison, communication configuration evidence, signed FAT/SAT test records, time-sync verification, and completed witness test data sheets. Utilities use it to verify the SCADA system meets interconnection agreement requirements before authorizing commercial operation."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How far before COD should we schedule the utility witness test?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Schedule the utility witness 4 to 6 weeks before your target COD date. Most utilities require 2 to 4 weeks of advance notice, and you need buffer time for first-pass failures and reschedules. Running a 24- to 48-hour pre-witness verification period before the scheduled witness date is essential to confirm stable telemetry and catch time-sync issues early."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the most common reasons solar SCADA commissioning witness tests fail?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Point list mismatches are the leading cause of first-pass failures: wrong engineering units, stale tag names, or incorrect scaling factors in the RTU. Time-sync errors are the second most common cause, typically from GPS lock loss or NTP misconfiguration. Both are preventable with a structured pre-witness verification step 24 to 48 hours before the witness appointment."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Which communication protocol does the utility require for solar SCADA commissioning?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "DNP3 (IEEE Std 1815-2012) is the dominant protocol for bulk electric system interconnections in North America. Distribution-level DER interconnections increasingly require IEEE 2030.5 (SEP 2), particularly in California and FERC Order 2222 aggregation contexts. The required protocol, address map, and response mode are defined in the interconnection agreement's SCADA exhibit. Confirm the current exhibit version before configuring the RTU."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does FERC Order 842 affect solar SCADA commissioning witness tests?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. FERC Order 842 requires all new generating facilities to have primary frequency response capability, and this must be demonstrated during commissioning. During solar SCADA commissioning for interconnection, the utility witness includes a frequency-Watt response test where inverters must respond to an under-frequency condition and the SCADA system must record and report the response with sub-second timestamps."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between SAT and utility witness testing?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The SAT is conducted by the commissioning team to verify the SCADA system works as designed. Utility witness testing is a separate formal milestone where a utility representative verifies the system meets interconnection agreement requirements. SAT evidence forms part of the witness pack, but the utility witness is a distinct gated step with its own sign-off authority and schedule."
        }
      }
    ]
